node.text: Something my friend and I do when we have a problem causing us anxiety is, when we’re ready to face it but not in a confrontational way, we write it into a story. If it’s a person, change their name, if it’s a thing, give it a name, and then make it the villain. And then make you, the protagonist, solve it. If you’re having trouble getting over an ex? Slap a Chad over his name tag and make him the dragon witch of your nightmares, ready to be slain by the sword of “I don’t care!”. It really helps me personally work out my problems, but I suggest not doing this until you’ve done some of the items on this list because this is more of a “When I think I’m ready to face my problems, this is the cut scene, the training exercise, the check point, the game’s way of telling me that I need a game plan.”
@mattfrancey why I’m always busy doing something since day one

Yes! I knit to relieve anxiety but it only works because I knit while watching YouTube videos or something so I'm not thinking about anything other than my knitting and what's going on in the video, for some reason I need both instead of just the video lol. Helps me though

I personally find that doing two things at once can help. For example I do cross stitch while listening to an audio book or watching a TV show. Using both parts of my brain means there’s no room left for anything else.
@can.i.bee.lamer thank you ❤️

There's this app I have called What's Up? that has a section meant to help ground you when you're feeling anxious. It makes you think of a certain number of a certain type of thing to distract your mind.
Thank you for this

@luisitocabezon
I kickbox when I'm anxious. Or I go to an intense yoga class. I get the endorphins and my brain can only think about the patterns and getting it right. No room for obsessing.

The point of those activities isn't to give you time to think, it's to fill your mind so you don't have any brain power left to be anxious. This is why playing video games is relaxing, it takes over your brain. If knitting doesn't hold your attention, find something that does hold it.
That’s how I am, I find myself getting more anxious doing relaxing activities. My brain has nothing to hold on to so it harps on the negative thoughts
I’ve been told to do yoga and breathing exercise to cure my anxiety
If I do math I get worse
Yes this is so great!!! Thinking complex thoughts works best for me. I like to do music theory exercises (list the circle of 5ths, go through flats and sharps in each key, etc).
@jmurdah so great. And so true.

i legitimately go crazy when I try to do something “relaxing”. I freak out
